Meet Gladys Karina, a program manager at X, Alphabet's moonshot factory. Originally from Ecuador, Gladys Karina is pictured wearing a toquilla woven straw hat, a traditional Ecuadorian art. “Knowing where I come from is a key part of knowing who I am and what I stand for. No matter how difficult the obstacle, I know that I do not stand alone. Supported by the strength of our forefathers and inspired by the potential of our descendants, our cultural heritage is a beautiful ode to our history and a lighthouse for our future. We all are living legacies."

Meet Marine Veteran Elizabeth Jones, another amazing Google Student Veterans of America scholar. After leaving the corps in 2007, she became an electrical engineer. Today she works as a systems engineer on anti-submarine warfare systems to protect American soldiers at sea. Meet Jen Holland, a program manager on our education team who works on products like Google Classroom and Expeditions (a virtual field trip app for schools). "The biggest joy I get is going into a class and seeing the magic of Expeditions take over. The students are totally engaged without even realizing it and are so immersed in these tours and asking incredible inquisitive questions. The teachers can hardly believe what they are seeing and the smiles on their faces is just priceless. That's what learning should look like every day."

Meet Adriana, a Google software engineer, who up until 4 years ago today, lived in Candelaria de Naranjo, a small town in Costa Rica. Wearing a traditional Costa Rican dress, Adriana talked about her favorite food (her mom's "olla de carne") and one of her biggest moments at Google: “I went to a recruiting event at a high school in Costa Rica. After the talk, one of the students approached me and said, ‘I wouldn’t have imagined in my wildest dreams that someone from our hometown could work at Google. This is awesome, I now want to work for NASA and I think I can do it.’ That moment made me feel like I’ve come so far, and that I’m helping people see it is possible to work for big companies, no matter where you’re born.”

After leading the effort to ensure a woman would appear on U.S. currency for the first time, Rios is now focused on her Teachers Righting History initiative which gives teachers and students access to the database so that they can recognize the contributions that women have made to American history. Can a cell phone and machine learning help stop deforestation? Nonprofit @rainforestcx and the Tembé tribe from the central Amazon hope so. They’re transforming Android phones into solar-powered acoustic monitoring devices that are hidden in trees. Using TensorFlow, Google’s open-source machine learning tool, they can analyze the audio data collected from the phones and identify sounds of illegal logging in the area. See our story today to learn more about how this tribe is using technology to save their forest.

Meet Laura, our head of Latino engagement. "Women at Google are fierce! We are leaders who are redefining the face of tech. I am especially proud to be a Latina at Google because our life journey has often called for a little more grit and a lot of resilience. Many of us were the first to attend college or to move away from home. I am one of the few Latinas, maybe the only one, with a dual MBA/MPA from Harvard. In 2005, I was the only Latino serving as a Congressional Legislative Director for a period of time. It can be hard to be the only one and to have the courage to speak your truth. The Latinas here at Google have their own remarkable stories. The result is an incredible group of Latinas who persevere and advance our community's economic and social well-being. I couldn't imagine being on this path with anyone else!"

Meet Hector. Born in Venezuela and raised in Miami, Hector now works on our philanthropy team, Google.org, where he manages programs across Latin America, and supports our disaster relief giving and volunteer work globally. The most influential person in his life is his dad: “As a first-generation immigrant, he taught me about risk-taking and tenacity. He’s always balanced family life with the needs of the community. Whether it meant taking immigrant families into our home while they got on their feet, working with the homeless to help them rehabilitate, or volunteering to feed the needy at nearby shelters, my dad never turned down a chance show grace to those in the margins.”

Meet Olivia, a Staffing Services Associate at Google. Raised on the Oneida Indian Reservation in Wisconsin, Olivia now works at our Mountain View headquarters and is a member of the Google American Indian Network. Wearing earrings and a necklace made of wampum, a traditional bead made out of quahog shells native to the East Coast, she says, “Native Americans have remained resilient through a long history of forced relocation by our ability to creatively adapt our values and ways to changing environments. Oneida’s traditional homelands are in New York, and like quahog shells, we represent our cultural legacies wherever we go. I’m inspired by incorporating my culture into my daily life, from simply wearing wampum jewelry to working with the Google American Indian Network, to make an impact in Native communities across the country. Our heritage is a strong fire that has been kept alive and protected through each generation and I am so honored to celebrate it today.”

Meet Kevin, a user experience engineer for YouTube who also oversees the intranet presence for the Black Googler Network. Kevin says overcoming obstacles such as homelessness has helped him in his role to "emphasize empathy and thorough, outside-in thinking." And of the people who supported him along the way, he says they inspired him to know that "it doesn't matter where I started, but where I finish."

Today, Google.org announced its two-year, $50 million commitment to support innovative nonprofits that use technology to close the global education gap. One of these organizations is @PBStoryweaver, which uses an open-sourced platform to translate books for students around the world, like these students in Bengaluru, India.

Originally from Mexico City, Alberto is now an industrial design creative lead for Hardware at our Mountain View headquarters. Above he’s holding an original molcajete from his grandma, a tool used to make salsa from scratch. On his work, he says, “Growing up in a vibrant city with a mix of cultures (the hyper-modern and the ancient traditions co-existing), shaped my method of problem-solving and tackling challenges. One of the most interesting challenges of my job is translating Google’s brand values—being “approachable,” for example—into physical objects.”
